<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-circles-chords-and-tangents-in-real-life" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Circles, Chords, and Tangents in Real Life</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.3 Circles, Chords and Tangents
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Apply angles chords and tangents to real life situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    12 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    Learners discover the size of the circle that fits in the gap between three mutually tangent circles of equal radius, building intuition for Descartes' circle theorem.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Provide each group with three identical circular objects (e.g. 50 shilling coins, all of the same denomination) and a piece of paper. Ask groups to trace around the three coins arranged so each touches the other two, then try to draw the largest circle that fits in the central gap. Prompt: <em>How do the sizes seem to compare? Can you express your answer as a fraction of the radius of one coin?</em> After groups share results, move to the structured instruction to formalise the pattern.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <title>Three Sodas and the Gap Circle</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Three soda bottles, each with a circular base of radius 4 cm, are placed on a flat surface so that each bottle touches the other two.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-bottle-caps">
                <caption>Three equally size bottle caps</caption>
                <image>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                            \tkzDefPoint(2,3){A}
                            \begin{scope}[shift=(A)]
                            \tkzDefPoint(60:5){B}
                            \tkzDefPoint(0:5){C}
                            \end{scope}

                            \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{MAB}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{MBC}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(C,A)\tkzGetPoint{MCA}

                            \tkzDrawCircles[thick](A,MAB B,MBC C,MCA)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C)
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Trace the base of each bottle onto paper (or use three equal coins). Arrange the three circles so each touches the other two.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        A packing company wants to know what size circular padding to put in the gap between the three bottles to keep them from knocking against each other during transport. Draw the largest circle that fits in the gap between the three bottles.
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            Here we have drawn the largest circle that fits in the gap.
                        </p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-bottle-caps-soln">
                                <caption>Three equally size bottle caps</caption>
                                <image>
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\d}{8} % diameter of the three circles
                                            \tkzDefPoint(2,3){A} % Setup equilateral ABC
                                            \begin{scope}[shift=(A)]
                                            \tkzDefPoint(60:\d){B}
                                            \tkzDefPoint(0:\d){C}
                                            \end{scope}

                                            \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{MAB}
                                            \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{MBC}
                                            \tkzDefMidPoint(C,A)\tkzGetPoint{MCA}
                                            \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{O}
                                            \tkzInterLC[near](O,A)(A,MAB)\tkzGetFirstPoint{D}

                                            \tkzDrawCircles[thick](A,MAB B,MBC C,MCA)
                                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,D)
                                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Measure the radius of your gap circle, and then try and compute a formula for the radius of the gap circle in terms of the radius of the bottles.
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            As shown in <xref ref="fig-bottle-caps-soln-formula"/>, we first recognise that the centre of the gap circle is the circumcentre and the orthocentre of the triangle formed by the centres of the three bottles.
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-bottle-caps-soln-formula">
                            <caption>Three equally size bottle caps</caption>
                            <image>
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\d}{8} % diameter of the three circles
                                        \tkzDefPoint(2,3){A} % Setup equilateral ABC
                                        \begin{scope}[shift=(A)]
                                        \tkzDefPoint(60:\d){B}
                                        \tkzDefPoint(0:\d){C}
                                        \end{scope}

                                        \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{MAB}
                                        \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{MBC}
                                        \tkzDefMidPoint(C,A)\tkzGetPoint{MCA}
                                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{O}
                                        \tkzInterLC[near](O,A)(A,MAB)\tkzGetFirstPoint{D}

                                        \tkzDrawCircles[thick](A,MAB B,MBC C,MCA)
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,D)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,O,D)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints(A,B,C)
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[right, xshift=10pt](O){$O$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[above](MAB){$X$}
                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)

                                        \tkzDrawSegments[teal](O,D)
                                        \tkzDrawSegments(D,A MAB,O)
                                        \tkzMarkRightAngle(O,MAB,A)

                                        \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.8](O,A,B)
                                        \tkzFillAngle[opacity=0.5, color=red!50, size=0.8](O,A,B)
                                        \tkzLabelAngle[pos=2](O,A,B){$30^\circ$}
                                        \tkzLabelSegment[pos=0.5, below right](O,D){$r$}
                                        \tkzLabelSegment[pos=0.5, sloped, below](D,A){$4$}
                                        \tkzLabelSegment[pos=0.5, sloped, above](MAB,A){$4$}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                        <p>
                            We thus have <m>\angle XAC = \angle BAC / 2 = 30^\circ</m>, and <m>OX</m> perpendicular to <m>AB</m>. <m>AX = 4</m> since it is a bottle cap radius, and if we let <m>OD = r</m> be the radius of the gap circle, then <m>AO = 4 + r</m>. By the right triangle <m>OXD</m>:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \cos 30^\circ \amp = \frac{4}{4+r} </mrow>
                                <mrow> 4+r \amp = 4 \times \frac{2}{\sqrt{3}} </mrow>
                                <mrow>r \amp = \frac{8}{\sqrt{3}} - 4 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \frac{8\sqrt{3}}{3} - 4 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp \approx 0.619 \text{ cm} </mrow>
                            </md>
                            If we had started with bottles of radius <m>R</m>, we would have found the gap circle radius to be <md>r = \frac{8\sqrt{3}}{3}R - R </md>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        What would happen to the gap circle if the three bottles were larger? Would the ratio between the gap radius and the bottle radius change? Why or why not?
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            Divide the formula by <m>R</m> gives:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \frac{r}{R} \amp = \frac{2\sqrt{3}}{3} - 1 </mrow>
                            </md>
                            This is independent of the bottle radius, so the ratio between the gap radius and the bottle radius does not change. The gap circle scales in size with the bottles.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    Provide general guidance for solving circle geometry problems in real life.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Tie these tips in to the activity problem.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            When working with circle geometry problems in real life, it's really important to:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Draw a clear diagram, labelling all known and unknown lengths and angles.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Avoid making assumptions about the diagram that aren't justified by the problem statement. Don't make a triangle equilateral unless you are told it is.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Add construction points / lines / circles to your diagram if they help.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Make sure you give your answer in the correct units.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight>

